{
"overall_read": "This reads as a personal affirmation or boundary-setting mantra, likely from a therapeutic or spiritual context. It has the quality of a deliberate, conscious declaration of emotional autonomy—a way to reclaim one's energy from codependent or enmeshed dynamics. The language is somatic and metaphorical ('field,' 'frequency'), which feels both grounded and abstract. It lands as earnest and self-protective, but also slightly brittle, as if the speaker is still in the process of convincing themselves of their right to detach. The repetition of 'I am' makes it an active, present-tense practice rather than a passive wish.",
"where_it_helps": "This statement is most helpful for people who tend to overfunction emotionally, absorbing the stress or dysregulation of others (e.g., in caregiving roles, high-conflict relationships, or helping professions). It can serve as a quick cognitive reset during interpersonal overwhelm, reinforcing boundaries against guilt, over-responsibility, or emotional contagion. It also supports mindful detachment in settings where empathy without boundaries leads to burnout—such as therapy, coaching, or parenting.",
"where_it_could_mislead": "It could mislead someone into dismissing legitimate, shared emotional reality, especially in close relationships where mutual support or vulnerability is needed. Over-reliance on this framing might justify emotional withdrawal or avoidance rather than healthy engagement. It also risks pathologizing normal empathy or presenting all emotional absorption as harmful, when some may be part of consensual connection. The language of 'handing that frequency back' could foster a subtle judgment of others' emotions as contaminants, rather than as information or bids for connection."
